Haiti has put measures in place to limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19).
For information on how to return to the UK from Haiti, see Return to the UK
If you live in the UK and are currently travelling abroad, you are strongly advised to return now, where and while there are still commercial routes available. Many airlines have suspended flights and major airports are closing, preventing flights from leaving.
Local measures
On 19 March the Haitian President announced a national state of emergency and detailed measures aimed at tackling the spread of the Coronavirus. These measures have been extended until 20 May. We strongly advise all British citizens in Haiti to follow the measures set out by President Moise in full. Key measures include:
A curfew between 2000 and 0500, effective from Friday 20 March;
Citizens to stay at home and limit their movements to essential movements only;
Schools, universities and factories and places of worship to close until further notice;
A ban on all events/meetings of more than 10 people;
The wearing of facemasks in public has also been announced.
A 14 day quarantine for anyone entering the country.
Entry and borders
As of midnight on March 20, all ports, airports, and borders have closed with the exception of transportation of merchandise, and the captains and the pilots of cargo vessels/planes.
This exclusion does not apply to: Haitian citizens and permanent residents or their immediate families, or diplomats.
Further information
Information is available from the Ministry of Health (Ministere de la Sante publique et de la Population (in French and Kreyol).
You should comply with any screening or quarantine requirements imposed by the Haitian authorities.
See the TravelHealthPro website for further advice on travel abroad and reducing spread of respiratory viruses during the COVID-19 pandemic.
